 1 NA NA NA NA NA\n26 NA NA NA  0 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA\n27 NA  0  0 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA  0\n28 NA NA NA NA  0 NA NA NA NA NA NA\n29 NA  1  1 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA\n30 NA NA NA NA NA  1 NA NA NA NA NA\n31 NA NA NA  0 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA\n32 NA NA NA  0 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA\n33 NA NA NA NA NA NA  1 NA NA NA NA\n34 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA  1\n35 NA NA NA NA NA NA  0 NA NA NA NA\n36 NA NA NA NA NA NA  0 NA NA NA NA\n37  1 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA\n38 NA NA NA NA  1 NA NA NA NA NA NA\n39 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA  0\n40 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA  1\n41 NA NA NA  1 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA\n42 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA  1\n43 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA  1 NA\n44 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA  1  1 NA NA\n45 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA  1\n46 NA  1  1 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA\n47 NA NA NA NA  1 NA NA NA NA NA NA\n48 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA  0  0 NA NA\n49  0 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA\n50 NA NA NA  0 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA\n51 NA  0  1 NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Model Building","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Method Description**\nThe Rasch model is a unidimensional IRT model that assumes all items measure a single latent trait (e.g., ability or proficiency). The `mirt` package is used to fit the model to the `irt_data_wide` dataset, which is in wide format, with each row representing a player and each column representing an item (constellation). The Metropolis-Hastings Robbins-Monro (MHRM) algorithm is used for estimation, which is suitable for sparse data matrices. The latent trait distribution is assumed to be Gaussian (normal).\n\n**Fit the Rasch Model** :The `model = 1` argument specifies a single latent trait, `itemtype = \"Rasch\"` indicates the use of the Rasch model, `method = \"MHRM\"` specifies the estimation algorithm, and `sparse = TRUE` indicates that the data matrix is sparse.\n\n**Summary of Model**: The summary output shows factor loadings and the proportion of variance explained by the latent trait for each item.\n\n**Test Information Function**: The test information function shows how much information each item provides about the latent trait at different levels of the trait.\n\n**Plot Item Characteristic Curves (ICCs)**:ICCs show the probability of a correct response to an item at different levels of the latent trait.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Fit the Rasch model using the mirt package with sparse data\nfitRasch <- mirt(irt_data_wide, model = 1, itemtype = \"Rasch\", method = \"MHRM\", sparse = TRUE)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-01-09T11:39:48.389187Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-01-09T11:39:48.391455Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-01-09T11:39:51.990244Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":5,"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Stage 3 = 78, CDLL = -18.5, AR(1.26) = [0.15], gam = 0.0068, Max-Change = 0.0009\n\nCalculating log-likelihood...\n","output_type":"stream"}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"fitRasch","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-01-09T11:39:51.993638Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-01-09T11:39:51.995488Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-01-09T11:39:52.017625Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":6,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"\nCall:\nmirt(data = irt_data_wide, model = 1, itemtype = \"Rasch\", method = \"MHRM\", \n    sparse = TRUE)\n\nFull-information item factor analysis with 1 factor(s).\nConverged within 0.001 tolerance after 78 MHRM iterations.\nmirt version: 1.41 \nM-step optimizer: NR1 \nLatent density type: Gaussian \nAverage MH acceptance ratio(s): 0.195 \n\nLog-likelihood = -39.33933, SE = 0.007\nEstimated parameters: 12 \nAIC = 102.6787\nBIC = 125.1331; SABIC = 87.48629\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Model Convergence and Fit**\n\nThe output indicates that the model converged after 78 MHRM iterations, with a convergence criterion of 0.001. The log-likelihood of the model is -39.34, with a standard error of 0.007, suggesting a good fit. The model estimated a total of 12 parameters.\n\nInformation criteria are provided to evaluate model fit:\n- AIC (Akaike Information Criterion): 102.68\n- BIC (Bayesian Information Criterion): 125.13\n- SABIC (Sample-Size Adjusted BIC): 87/59\n\nThe average Metropolis-Hastings acceptance ratio is 0.195, which is a measure of the efficiency of the sampling algorithm.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"summary(fitRasch)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-01-09T11:39:52.020795Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-01-09T11:39:52.022562Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-01-09T11:39:52.041732Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":7,"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"      F1     h2\n5  0.105 0.0111\n10 0.105 0.0111\n12 0.105 0.0111\n13 0.105 0.0111\n8  0.105 0.0111\n1  0.105 0.0111\n9  0.105 0.0111\n4  0.105 0.0111\n6  0.105 0.0111\n3  0.105 0.0111\n11 0.105 0.0111\n\nSS loadings:  0.122 \nProportion Var:  0.011 \n\nFactor correlations: \n\n   F1\nF1  1\n","output_type":"stream"}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Summary of Model**\n\nThe summary output shows factor loadings and the proportion of variance explained by the latent trait for each item. All items have a factor loading of 0.105 on the first factor (F1), and the proportion of variance (h2) explained by the latent trait is 0.0111 for all items. This indicates that the items are consistently measuring the same underlying trait.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Test information function for random items\nplot(fitRasch, type = 'info', items = c(2, 22, 123, 163))","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-01-09T11:39:52.044897Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-01-09T11:39:52.046573Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-01-09T11:39:52.472424Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":8,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"image/png":"iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAA0gAAANICAIAAAByhViMAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAg\nAElEQVR4nOzdeXxU5aHG8ffMkkz2ZCYbCSQkYd8EW